{"title_page": "Bispham, Blackpool", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Bispham, West Lancashire}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n |static_image=          Bispham_Seafront_with_Norbreck_Castle_in_Distance_-_geograph.org.uk_-_33113.jpg\n |static_image_caption=  Bispham Seafront with Norbreck Castle in the distance\n |official_name=             Bispham\n |unitary_england=           [[Blackpool]]\n |lieutenancy_england=       [[Lancashire]]\n |region=                    North West England\n |country=                   England\n |coordinates = {{coord|53.852|-3.041|display=inline,title}}\n | population = 20,001\n | population_ref = [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]]\n |constituency_westminster=  [[Blackpool North and Cleveleys (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackpool North and Cleveleys]]\n |post_town=                 BLACKPOOL\n |postcode_area=             FY\n |postcode_district=         FY2\n |dial_code=                 01253\n |os_grid_reference=         SD309399<!-- NOT SURE WHERE THE EXACT CENTRE OF BISPHAM SHOULD BE, THIS IS POSSIBLY NOT TOTALLY ACCURATE -->\n |pushpin_map              = United Kingdom Blackpool\n |pushpin_map_caption      = Location in Blackpool\n }}\n\n'''Bispham''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u026a|s|p|\u0259m}} is a village on the [[Fylde coast]] in [[Lancashire]], England, a mile and a half north of [[Blackpool]] town centre.\n\n==Geography and administration==\nThe village is part of the borough of Blackpool. To the south of Bispham is Warbreck, North Shore and [[Layton, Blackpool|Layton]], to the east is [[Carleton, Lancashire|Carleton]] and to the north is Norbreck and [[Thornton Cleveleys]] and to the west, the [[Irish Sea]]. The area is mostly urban. Bispham was formerly in the [[Blackpool North and Fleetwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackpool North and Fleetwood parliamentary constituency]], but, as of the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] forms part of the [[Blackpool North and Cleveleys (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackpool North and Cleveleys constituency]] whose [[Member of Parliament|M.P.]] is [[Paul Maynard]].\n\nThe village is in the [[North West England (European Parliament constituency)|North West England European parliament constituency]].\n\nBispham has three Blackpool Council [[Ward (country subdivision)|electoral wards]]: Bispham, Greenlands and Ingthorpe.<ref name=\"BC001\">{{cite web | title = Ward map | publisher = Blackpool Council | url = http://www.blackpool.gov.uk/Services/A-F/CouncillorsInformation/WardMap.htm | accessdate =12 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nThe population at the [[United Kingdom Census 2001]] was 19,165, 13.41% of the population of Blackpool (142,900), with 3,873 residents aged between 0 and 17 years old (20.21%), 4,329 aged 65 and over (22.58%) and 10,963 between the ages of 18 and 64 (57.21%).<ref name=\"blackpoolresidents\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blackpool.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/953ABC47-4FC2-498F-A513-E919B3CE44BF/0/ThedistributionofresidentswithinBlackpoolv2.pdf |title=The distribution of Residents within Blackpool |date=July 2004 |publisher=Blackpool Council |format=PDF |accessdate=5 November 2008 }}{{dead link|date=August 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> At the census 2011 the overall population using the same three wards increased to 20,001.\n\nPopulation by ward \u2013\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Ward !! Population\n|-\n|Bispham || 6,375\n|-\n|Greenlands || 6,865\n|-\n|Ingthorpe || 6,761\n|}\n\n==Village history==\nA 12,000-year-old animal skeleton (the Carleton Elk) found with barbed arrowheads near [[Blackpool Sixth Form College]] in 1970 provided the first evidence of humans living on [[The Fylde]] as far back as the [[Palaeolithic]] era.<ref name=\"amounderness\">{{cite web |title=Who were the Setantii? |publisher=amounderness.com |url=http://www.amounderness.com/site/setantii.htm |accessdate=26 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080330043117/http://www.amounderness.com/site/setantii.htm |archivedate=30 March 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref> The Fylde was also home to a British tribe, the [[Setantii]] (the \"dwellers in the water\") a sub-tribe of the [[Brigantes]], who from about AD80 were controlled by [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] from their fort at Dowbridge, [[Kirkham, Lancashire|Kirkham]]. During the Roman occupation, the area was covered by oak forests and bog land.\n\nBispham, known until 1910 as Bispham-with-Norbreck,<ref name=\"BH53229\">{{cite journal| last = Farrer| first = William|author2=Brownbill, J| title = Townships: Bispham with Norbreck | journal = A History of the County of Lancaster| volume = 7| pages =246\u2013247| publisher = British History Online| year = 1912| url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=53229&strquery=Bispham| accessdate =12 January 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"BH53228\"/> was originally a village in its own right, pre-dating the town of Blackpool by several hundred years. In 1066 Bispham was part of [[Tostig Godwinson]], the Earl of [[Northumbria]]'s, Lordship of [[Amounderness]].<ref name=\"BH53189\">{{cite journal| last = Farrer| first = William|author2=Brownbill, J| title = Amounderness hundred: Introduction and map| journal = A History of the County of Lancaster| volume = 7| pages =68\u201371| publisher = British History Online| year = 1912| url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=53189| accessdate =12 January 2008}}</ref> It is featured in the [[Domesday Book]] of 1086 as '''Biscopham'''.<ref name=\"BH53229\"/><ref name=\"BH53189\"/><ref name=\"DDB001\">{{cite web| title = Domesday Book online \u2013 Lancashire| publisher = domesdaybookonline| url = http://www.domesdaybook.co.uk/lancashire.html| accessdate =12 January 2008}}</ref> (meaning ''Bishop's estate'' or ''Bishop's house'') Many of the settlements and villages on [[The Fylde]] were [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] settlements. Some though were 9th and 10th century [[Viking]] place names. The Vikings and Anglo-Saxons seem to have co-existed peacefully with some Anglo-Saxon and Viking place names later being joined together\u2014such as Bispham-with-Norbreck.<ref name=\"VB1252\">{{cite news|title=Blackpool History|publisher=Blackpool Tourist Office|url=http://www.visitblackpool.com/resources/files/125_2_Blackpool_History.pdf|accessdate=18 March 2007|format=PDF}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name=\"BT001\">{{cite news|title=Historic Blackpool: Blackpool's History |publisher=Blackpool Tourist Office |url=http://www.blackpooltourism.com/blackpool-history |accessdate=18 March 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080131233124/http://www.blackpooltourism.com/blackpool-history |archivedate=31 January 2008 }}</ref> Bispham having the Anglo-Saxon place name ''ham''<ref name=\"LUOAC\">{{cite web|title=English Place Names |publisher=[[University of Liverpool]] Walking Club |url=http://www.luoac.co.uk/other/English.php |accessdate=12 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215115350/http://www.luoac.co.uk/other/english.php |archivedate=15 December 2007 }}</ref> and Norbreck having the Viking place name, ''breck''. Bispham-with-Norbreck comprised three hamlets \u2013 Great (or Greater) Bispham, Little Bispham and Norbreck, with Anchorsholme (then Angersholme) part of Norbreck. Although the three hamlets were originally part of the Lordship of Amounderness, they were later divided with the [[Moiety (kinship)|moiety]] of Little Bispham and Norbreck being given to [[Shrewsbury Abbey]] and Great Bispham to the Lord of Warrington.<ref name=\"BH53229\"/>\n\n''Great Bispham'' was a part of the Lordship of Layton. In 1539, it was bought by John Browne, who sold it to Thomas Fleetwood in 1550.\n\nThe moiety of ''Little Bispham and Norbreck'' was given to the monks of [[Shrewsbury Abbey]] by Roger of [[Poitou]]. In the early 12th century [[Henry I of England|Henry I]] ordered Stephen Count of Mortain to hold the moiety \"free and quit of all customs, pleas and suits of the [[Hundred (country subdivision)|hundred court]]. A few years after, [[David I of Scotland]] confirmed the moiety \"to be held as freely as in the time of his predecessors.\" In about 1270 the abbot and convent of Shrewsbury granted Little Bispham and Norbreck to the Abbot and convent of [[Dieulacres Abbey]], who held the adjoining Rossall estate. After the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries]], it was granted as part of Rossall estate, in 1553 to Thomas Fleetwood. Thus by then all three hamlets were owned by Thomas Fleetwood.<ref name=\"BH53229\"/>\n\nIn 1326 the spelling of the village was '''Byspham'''. Bispham and [[Poulton-le-Fylde]] were the two main populated centres in The Fylde in 1500, though the area was sparsely populated.<ref name=\"Genuki\">{{cite news|title=Blackpool, Lancashire genealogy|publisher=[[GENUKI]]|year=2006|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Blackpool/history.html|accessdate=4 April 2007}}</ref>\n\nIt was in Bispham that the first mention of \"Blackpool\" appeared, found in the Register of [[Bispham Parish Church]] in 1602 with the christening record of a child born on 22 September to a couple who lived \"''on the bank of the Black Pool''\".<ref name=\"Genuki\"/> In the 17th century The Fylde coast was divided into three parishes\u2014Bispham, Poulton-le-Fylde and Lytham. The parish of Bispham covered modern-day Blackpool and Thornton Cleveleys and comprised the townships of Bispham-with-Norbreck and Layton-cum-Warbreck.<ref name=\"BH53228\">{{cite journal| last = Farrer| first = William|author2=Brownbill, J| title = The parish of Bispham| journal = A History of the County of Lancaster| volume = 7| pages =242\u2013246| publisher = British History Online| year = 1912| url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=53228&strquery=Bispham| accessdate =12 January 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"VB1252\"/><ref name=\"MUK001\">{{cite web| title = Lancashire Parishes\u2014Distribution of Lancashire Parishes in the 17th Century| publisher = Papillon Graphics| work = Virtual Encyclopaedia of Greater Manchester| url = http://www.manchester2002-uk.com/maps/lancs-parishes-map.html#| accessdate = 12 January 2008| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080118204247/http://www.manchester2002-uk.com/maps/lancs-parishes-map.html%23| archivedate = 18 January 2008| df = dmy-all}}</ref> In 1877 a detached part of Little Carleton (then known as Horsemans Hill) was placed in Bispham,<ref name=\"BH53229\"/><ref name=\"VB1252\"/><ref name=\"BH53224\">{{cite journal| last = Farrer| first = William|author2=Brownbill, J| title = Townships: Carleton| journal = A History of the County of Lancaster| volume = 7| pages = 228\u2013231| publisher = British History Online| year = 1912| url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=53224| accessdate =17 November 2008}}</ref> then in 1883 the area known as ''Bispham Hawes'', which was at the south end of Layton, was detached from Bispham and added to Layton. The population of Bispham-with-Norbreck in 1901 was 985.<ref name=\"BH53229\"/>\n\nAlthough the village centre used to be thatched with a number of pre-19th-century houses, it was redesigned in the 1960s; only two of the old houses remain. Much of the housing today is of the design style consistent with that of the 1930s to the 1950s.\n\n==Modern Bispham==\nThe area is mostly residential with two main shopping areas. The main road at the hub of the village, Red Bank Road, houses a number of high street stores such as [[Sainsbury's]] supermarket. The main shopping area in Bispham is split into two distinct parts. Firstly, from the top of Red Bank Road at the junction with [[A584 road|Queens Promenade]], running halfway down Red Bank Road toward Bispham [[fire station]]. This area contains a mixture of local and tourist businesses including a relatively large number of restaurants, as well as a number of [[takeaway]]s and [[fashion design|designer wear]] shops. The other shopping area is based around what is known locally as \"the village\" which is the area beyond Devonshire Road roundabout behind Bispham [[Police Station]], where the shops are sited around a large outdoor car park. The village area also contains the handful of original cottages remaining in Bispham. There are also small shopping areas on Ashfield Road, Moor Park Avenue and Bispham Road.\n\n===Religion===\n[[File:BisphamParishChurch01.jpg|thumb|275px|Bispham Parish Church, All Hallows]]\nThere are two [[Church of England]] Parish churches\u2014[[Bispham Parish Church]], All Hallows Road, and Greenlands St. Anne church, Salmesbury Avenue and one Catholic Parish Church, St. Bernadette's church, on Devonshire Road. Other churches include The Gate Community Church, Bispham United Reformed Church, Springfield Greenlands Methodist Church, and Cavendish Road Congregational Church. An additional Methodist Church on Beaufort Avenue closed in 2017.\n\n[[Bispham Parish Church]] has an original Norman doorway<ref name=\"BH53228\"/> and is the Mother church of Blackpool.<ref name=\"BPC001\">{{cite web| title = Welcome to Bispham Parish Church| publisher = [[Bispham Parish Church]]| url = http://www.bisphamparishchurch.co.uk/| accessdate = 10 September 2007| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929090529/http://www.bisphamparishchurch.co.uk/| archive-date = 29 September 2007| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref> Greenlands, St Anne has an active healing ministry.<ref name=\"GSA001\">{{cite web| title = Healing Ministry| publisher = Greenlands, St Anne church| url = http://www.bisphamparishchurch.co.uk/| accessdate = 12 January 2008| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080306013120/http://www.bisphamparishchurch.co.uk/| archive-date = 6 March 2008| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref> Keajra Kadampa Buddhist Centre, a residential [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] centre and a member of the [[New Kadampa Tradition]] is located on Holmfield Road.\n\n===Education===\nThe village has several schools, including\n\n*'''Primary schools'''\n**Bispham Endowed Church of England Primary School, located on Bispham Road. The original school was housed in what is now the home of the local [[Sea Cadet]]s near to Devonshire Road roundabout. The school is connected to Bispham Parish Church, and the first school was founded in 1659.<ref name=\"BH53228\"/>\n**Kincraig Primary School, located on Kincraig Road close to [[Kincraig Lake Ecological Reserve]]. After an [[Office for Standards in Education|Ofsted]] report in 2001 in which inspectors described the school as having \"serious weaknesses\", the school rapidly improved and in 2004 it was named as one of the 200 most improved schools in England, as well as being the most improved school in Blackpool.<ref name=\"gazette1275236\">{{cite news| title = Things keep on getting better at most improved primary school| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 2 December 2005| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/Things-keep-on-getting-better.1275236.jp| accessdate =18 January 2008}}</ref> In 2007 the school was listed in the top 100 most improved schools in England.<ref name=\"gazette3561743\">{{cite news| last = Butler| first = Heather| title = New rise is a 'fantastic achievement'| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 2 December 2005| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/primary/New-rise-is-a-39fantastic.3561743.jp| accessdate =18 January 2008}}</ref>\n**Langdale Independent Preparatory School\n**Moor Park Primary School, located on Moor Park Avenue in the Moor Park area of Bispham.\n**Saint Bernadette's Catholic Primary School\n**Westcliff Primary School\n*'''[[Education in the United Kingdom#Secondary School|Secondary schools]]'''\n**[[Bispham High School Arts College]] (formally closed in 2014, demolished in January 2017)\n**[[Montgomery High School, Blackpool|Montgomery High School]]\n*'''[[Further education|Colleges]]'''\n**[[Blackpool and The Fylde College]] the large main campus of the college is located on Ashfield Road, Bispham.\n\n===Local attractions and amenities===\n[[File:Kincraig Lake01.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Part of Kincraig Lake, Kincraig Ecological Reserve]]The village has a few attractions, with the tram station and the highest cliffs on both The [[Fylde coast|Fylde Coast]] and the North West Coast. There are a number of hotels and guest houses mostly around the seaward end of Red Bank Road and on Queens Promenade. The Red Lion pub also houses a [[Premier Inn]].\n\nBispham has five of the fourteen [[Lancashire County Council]] designated Biological Heritage Sites (BHS) located in Blackpool,<ref name=\"BC002\">{{cite web| title =Biological Heritage Sites| publisher =Blackpool Council| url =http://www.blackpool.gov.uk/services/a-f/biologicalheritagesites/home.htm| accessdate =1 January 2008}}</ref> including [[Kincraig Lake Ecological Reserve]] which is located on Kincraig Road, with Kincraig lake and a wild fowl population, from which Kincraig Primary School takes its school crest.<ref name=\"KPS001\">{{cite web | title = Home Page| publisher = Kincraig Primary School| url = http://www.kincraig.blackpool.sch.uk/| accessdate =12 January 2008}}</ref>\n[[File:North Shore Golf Club01.jpg|thumb|250px|North Shore Golf course, with views of the Lake District hills, and the [[Norbreck Castle Hotel]] ]]\n[[File:Bispham Rock Gardens01.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Bispham Rock Gardens]] [[Bispham Rock Gardens]] is at the top of Knowle Hill on Devonshire Road and runs downhill toward the back of [[Bispham High School Arts College]] (formerly Greenlands High School for Girls), with views from the top toward [[Pendle Hill]], [[Beacon Fell Country Park, Lancashire|Beacon Fell]] and the [[Forest of Bowland|Bowland fells]].\n\n'''North Blackpool Pond Trail''' beginning at Holyoake Avenue and continuing as far as Moor Park Avenue covers a group of 23 ponds, a reed bed, a community orchard (on Salmesbury Avenue located at the former 'Higher Moor Farm') and a series of dykes /ditches, most of which are Biological Heritage Sites (important at a county level). A campaign by local residents and environmental groups led to the creation of a series of walks and interpretation boards along with a programme of events and volunteering opportunities though most of these 'walks' existed prior to their involvement and were produced by 'job creation' schemes. There are now significant opportunities for people to access and engage with the natural environment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.northwest.groundwork.org.uk/lancashire-west--wigan/news--events/news/2012/success-for-pond-trail.aspx |title=Success for North Blackpool Pond Trail |publisher=Northwest.groundwork.org.uk |date=7 February 2012 |accessdate=15 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130423202541/http://www.northwest.groundwork.org.uk/lancashire-west--wigan/news--events/news/2012/success-for-pond-trail.aspx |archivedate=23 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Moor Park, Blackpool|Moor Park]] runs adjoining Moor Park Avenue and Bispham Road. The park contains a children's playground, parkland, a (disused) [[bowling green]] and Moor Park Swimming Pool which is located in the northwest corner of the park. It has a 25-metre pool and a teaching pool.<ref name=\"B4ME001\">{{cite web | title = Moor Park Swimming Pool, Bristol Avenue | publisher = Blackpool 4 Me| url = http://www.blackpool4me.com/blackpool4me/community/yourarea/ingthorpeward/moor+park+swimming+pool.htm| accessdate =18 January 2008}}</ref> The ''Friends of Moor Park'' group was set up in January 2007 with the aim of restoring the park to its former glory including work on the footpaths through the park and the possibility of re-opening the disused bowling green as well as work on the children's playground.<ref name=\"Gazette1959284\">{{cite news| title = Residents' chance to enhance their park| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 5 January 2007| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/Residents39-chance-to-enhance-their.1959284.jp| accessdate =18 January 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"B4ME002\">{{cite web|title=Friends of Moor Park |publisher=Blackpool 4 Me |url=http://www.blackpool4me.com/blackpool4me/community/yourarea/ingthorpeward/friends+of+moor+park.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070515144714/http://www.blackpool4me.com/blackpool4me/community/yourarea/ingthorpeward/friends+of+moor+park.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 May 2007 |accessdate=18 January 2008 }}</ref> Other parks in Bispham include Cavendish Road Recreation Ground which has tennis courts, [[Association football|football]] and basketball areas and a bowling green, which has a Friends group\u2014''Friends of Cavendish Road Recreation Ground''.<ref name=\"B4ME003\">{{cite web | title = Cavendish Road Recreation Ground| publisher = www.blackpool.gov.uk| url = https://www.blackpool.gov.uk/Residents/Parks-and-community-facilities/Parks,-playgrounds-and-community-facilities/Cavendish-Road-Recreation-Ground.aspx| accessdate =21 January 2016}}</ref> In November 2007 with both funding and planning obtained, work started at Cavendish Road Recreation Ground on a new ''Kiddies playground'', aimed at children under seven years old; the new park opened in 2008.<ref name=\"B4ME004\">{{cite news | title = Fylde coast's latest fresh air fun park| newspaper = Blackpool Gazette| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/news/local/fylde-coast-s-latest-fresh-air-fun-park-1-426008| accessdate =21 January 2016}}</ref> Red Bank Bowling Green is located next to Sainsbury's and is owned by the adjoining Bispham Conservative Club. The green was originally a garden belonging to the house which is now the Conservative Club.<ref name=\"BCC001\">{{cite web|title=About us |publisher=Bispham Conservative Club |url=http://www.bisphamconclub.co.uk/page6.html |accessdate=18 January 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012173521/http://www.bisphamconclub.co.uk/page6.html |archivedate=12 October 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nBispham library was opened on 5 May 1938.<ref name=\"VB1252\"/> Bispham Hospital is a purpose built 40-bed rehabilitation unit, located on Ryscar Way for elderly patients from The Fylde coast as part of [[Blackpool Victoria Hospital]].<ref name=\"BFW001\">{{cite web|title=Bispham Hospital |publisher=Blackpool, Fylde and Wyre Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust |url=http://www.bfwhospitals.nhs.uk/hospitals/bispham/where.htm |accessdate=13 January 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026035849/http://www.bfwhospitals.nhs.uk/hospitals/bispham/where.htm |archivedate=26 October 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> [[Trinity - the hospice in the Fylde]] is a specialist [[palliative care]] service for adults and children located on Low Moor Road.<ref name=\"TTH001\">{{cite web| title = What is Trinity\u2014the hospice in the Fylde?| publisher = Trinity\u2014the hospice in the Fylde| url = http://www.trinitythehospice.inthefylde.org.uk/index.html| accessdate = 13 January 2008| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080305115246/http://www.trinitythehospice.inthefylde.org.uk/index.html| archivedate = 5 March 2008| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Public houses]] in Bispham include The Highlands, The Albion, the Red Lion, the Bispham Hotel and the Squirrel Hotel. There are also two wine bars, Xanders in ''the village'' and Maddisons on Red Bank Road.\n\nAdmiral Point on Queens Promenade is a luxury housing development in a Grade II listed building. It was originally [[Miners' Convalescent Home, Blackpool|The Miners Convalescent Home]] and was built by [[Bradshaw Gass & Hope]] between 1925 and 1927. It was opened by the Prince of Wales on 28 June 1927.<ref name=\"VB1252\"/><ref name=\"gazette1225442\">{{cite news| title = Premier league homes| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 19 October 2005| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/Premier-league-homes.1225442.jp| accessdate =23 August 2007}}</ref> The home, which for many years was empty was redeveloped into luxury homes by housebuilders Persimmon Homes and is now known as Admiral Point, with 47 apartments, together with 112 apartments and homes around the grounds, with two new six-storey apartment blocks built flanking the main building, and housing behind it.<ref name=\"gazette803268\">{{cite news| title = New name for famous old seafront landmark| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 8 June 2004| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/New-name-for-famous-old.803268.jp| accessdate =23 August 2007}}</ref> In February 2006 it was revealed that sales of apartments in, what the company described as \"the jewel in the crown\" at Admiral Point had helped Persimmon Homes to record profits, such was the popularity of the new properties in the Grade II listed building.<ref name=\"gazette1368688\">{{cite news | title = Prom flats sale delight| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 28 February 2006| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/business/Prom-flats-sale-delight.1368688.jp| accessdate =23 August 2007}}</ref> In October 2005 it was revealed that several high-profile [[Association football|footballers]], including former [[Premier League|Premiership]] player [[Robbie Fowler]] as well as [[Jonathan Macken]], [[Mads Timm]] and former player [[Lee Sharpe]] had bought apartments at Admiral Point.<ref name=\"gazette1225442\"/>\n\nBispham was also the home of British independent [[sports car]] manufacturer, [[TVR]], one of the main employers in Bispham, before production ceased in 2007 under owner [[Nikolai Smolenski]]. In May 2007 it was announced that Midlands based businessman, William Riley was proposing to bring back car production to Bispham, with two cars planned for production at a new purpose built factory, which would be on Bispham Technology Park, the [[MG XPower SV]] and another Premium [[MG XPower]] roadster and coupe.<ref name=\"gazette2858553\">{{cite news| title = Car deal so close| work = [[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 7 May 2007| url = http://www.blackpooltoday.co.uk/blackpoolnews?articleid=2858553| accessdate = 23 August 2007}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On 27 July 2007 Blackpool Council announced that the sports car production would begin within a matter of weeks, initially at part of the former TVR factory; with the company eventually moving to a purpose built factory which had already been leased from the council by William Riley.<ref name=\"gazette3067864\">{{cite news| title = Car production set to begin again in Blackpool| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 27 July 2007| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/Car-production-set-to-begin.3067864.jp| accessdate =23 August 2007}}</ref> Bispham Technology Park is a growing, modern, Office and Retail Park which is due to be expanded further in 2008 with the creation of Kincraig Business Park on a {{convert|3|acre|m2|adj=on}} site within the park together with an environmental project with green space area to protect wildlife including a pond.<ref name=\"gazette3506879\">{{cite news| title = 200 new jobs hope at business park| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 21 November 2007| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/200-new-jobs-hope-at.3506879.jp| accessdate =18 January 2008}}</ref> On 11 January 2008, local MP, [[Joan Humble]] cut the first sod at a ceremony at the new Kincraig Business Park with the first of forty plots being created at the new park having already been taken even before building work started.<ref name=\"gazette3665917\">{{cite news| last = Hyde| first = Nick| title = Hats off to start of new business era | work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 12 January 2008| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/Hats-off-to-start-of.3665917.jp| accessdate =18 January 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[Layton railway station (England)|Layton railway station]] was originally named Bispham railway station.<ref name=\"BH53224\"/> Both Bispham and Norbreck are separate areas of Blackpool. Although the two do come together annually for the ''Bispham and Norbreck Gala'' held in July of each year with a procession that winds through both Bispham and Norbreck starting and finishing at Bispham Gala fields,<ref name=\"gazette1632781\">{{cite news | title = Bispham and Norbreck Gala| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 17 July 2006| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/Bispham-and-Norbreck-gala.1632781.jp| accessdate =13 January 2008}}</ref> an open space which is owned by Blackpool Council with football pitches, a community centre, secure grazing area and with part of the land sublet to Blackpool [[Rugby union]] football club and a Golf Driving range. In 2007 local residents called for a covenant to be placed on the Gala fields to safeguard the land to be used for future galas.<ref name=\"gazette1632781\"/>\n\n===Blackpool Illuminations===\nRed Bank Road is at the Northern end of the world-famous [[Blackpool Illuminations]]. The area at Bispham Cliffs contains the famous tableaux displays, where there is a pathway for holidaymakers and locals to view the tableaux close up. The first animated tableaux were erected in 1932 running along the cliffs from North Shore to Bispham, and the Illuminations were extended to its current length running from Starr Gate to Red Bank Road at Bispham.<ref name=\"BT002\">{{cite web| title = History of the lights| publisher = Blackpool Tourism| url = http://www.blackpooltourism.com/?OBH=299&SCH=illuminations%20history&ID=0| accessdate =2 December 2007}}</ref> Some of the tableaux have sound and visual content that can only be viewed and heard by walking by them.\n[[File:Blackpool Tramway - Bispham depot headstone.jpg|200px|right|thumb|Headstone from Bispham depot]]\nThe tableaux also includes mixed media in the various large tableaux displays.<ref name=\"Gazette3138163\">{{cite news | title = Let there be lights| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 22 August 2007| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpool-illuminations-2007/Let-there-be-lights.3138163.jp| accessdate =2 December 2007}}</ref> The displays at the cliffs from North Shore to Bispham contain forty large tableaux holding more than 5,000 square metres in surface area. There is a pedestrian walkway running the length of the tableaux displays which are set back from the Promenade beyond the tramway. [[Blackpool Tramway]] runs along the entire length of the Illuminations and there are over one million lamps in the display.<ref name=\"VB305\">{{cite web| title = Illuminating facts| publisher = Visit Blackpool| url = http://www.visitblackpool.com/?OBH=305| accessdate =2 December 2007}}</ref> In 2007 the Egyptian tableau which includes Egyptian [[sarcophagus]], which eerily opens to reveal a mummified secret, returned after an overhaul. Also at Bispham on the clifftop was a new BBC Portal video screen.<ref name=\"Gazette3138184\">{{cite news | title = What's new?| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 22 August 2007| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpool-illuminations-2007/Whats-new.3138184.jp| accessdate =2 December 2007}}</ref> In January 2008 new plans were revealed to erect two new all year round, [[triumphal arch]]es at either end of the Illuminations, \"selling the Blackpool message\".<ref name=\"Gazette3670899\">{{cite news | last = Fleming| first = Craig| title = Begging bowl days are over| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 15 January 2008| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/Begging-bowl-days-are-over.3670899.jp| accessdate =16 January 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Blackpool Tramway===\n[[File:712 at Bispham.jpg|thumb|200px|A double-decker balloon tram on the promenade at Bispham]]\n[[Blackpool tramway]] runs along the length of the sea front at Bispham. In 1920 Blackpool Corporation took over the ''Blackpool & Fleetwood Tramroad Company'' gaining a further eight miles (13&nbsp;km) of track, and also three further depots including the Bispham Tram Depot on Red Bank Road, until it closed in 1966.<ref name=\"FTS001\">{{cite news|title=Blackpool Trams |publisher=Fylde Tramway Society |date=3 September 2004 |url=http://www.webtramways.com/fts/modules.php?op=modload&name=News&file=article&sid=20&mode=thread&order=0&thold=0&POSTNUKESID=bb03664365976e75a64321790f2f3237 |accessdate=3 November 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071019044630/http://www.webtramways.com/fts/modules.php?op=modload&name=News&file=article&sid=20&mode=thread&order=0&thold=0&POSTNUKESID=c9b8d0c8d415e0c052455f834bbbc29b |archivedate=19 October 2007 }}</ref> Built in 1898, Bispham Tram Depot had room to house 36 trams on six tracks, after being extended in 1914 by the Blackpool and Fleetwood Tramway Company. A substation was built to the side of depot. The depot was used to receive pantograph cars in 1928 and Brush cars in 1940. The depot closed on 27 October 1963 but used as a store, ''Alpic Cash & Carry'' until the mid-1970s.<ref name=\"BCC001\"/> The building was eventually demolished to make place for a [[Sainsbury's]] supermarket. The Depots headstone was installed at [[Crich]]'s [[National Tramway Museum]].\n\n==Notable people==\n''[[Emmerdale]]'' actress, [[Kelsey-Beth Crossley]] was a pupil at Bispham High School.,<ref name=\"blackpoolgazette070227\">{{cite news|title=Teenager makes TV soap debut|work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]|date=27 February 2007|url=http://www.blackpooltoday.co.uk/ViewArticle.aspx?SectionID=5442&ArticleID=2081817|accessdate=5 May 2007}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and former ''Emmerdale'' actress, [[Hayley Tamaddon]] was a pupil at Montgomery High School. ''[[Coronation Street]]'' actress, [[Violet Carson]], [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] lived in Bispham until her death in 1983. She is commemorated at Bispham Parish Church. Former ''[[Brookside]]'' and ''[[The Royle Family]]'' actor [[Ricky Tomlinson]], was born in Bispham on 26 September 1939.<ref>*{{IMDb name|id=0866870|name=Ricky Tomlinson}}</ref> English film-maker, [[Alan Entwistle (director)|Alan Entwistle]] was born in Bispham on 4 July 1961.<ref>{{IMDb name|id=1350291|name=Alan Entwistle}}</ref> The actor [[Tony Melody]] lived in the Greenlands area of Bispham for many years until his death in June 2008. Footballer [[George Berry (footballer)|George Berry]], born in Germany then his family moved to Bispham soon after he was born.<ref name=sentinel12509705>{{cite web|title=Stoke City legends: George Berry|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-legends-George-Berry/story-12509705-detail/story.html|publisher=The Sentinel|accessdate=28 January 2014|date=10 August 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221213316/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-legends-George-Berry/story-12509705-detail/story.html|archive-date=21 February 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \nFormer [[S Club 8]] singer [[Stacey McClean]] is from Bispham.<ref name=\"gazette5682905\">{{cite news|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/X-Factor-Stacey-is-flying.5682905.jp|title=X Factor Stacey is flying the Blackpool flag|last=Ettridge|first=Lisa|date=28 September 2009|work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]|accessdate=28 September 2009}}</ref> Prof [[Gerald R. Leighton]] was born in Bispham. Naturalised American actor [[John Mahoney]] was born here in 1940. [[Chris Richardson]], who is widely regarded as a local legend resides in the Bispham area.\n\n==Sport==\nNorth Shore Golf Club is located at the edge of Bispham with most of the golf course in Bispham. Tee Time Golf Centre Driving Range and nine-hole par three course is based on Fleetwood Road. Blackpool Rugby Union Football club are based in Bispham. Bispham Junior football Federation (BJFF) is based at Bispham Gala Fields. Blackpool Rangers also share this field.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last=Cunliffe|first=Norman|title=Uncle Tom's Cabin: Bispham's First Centre of Entertainment|publisher=Fylde Historical Society}}\n* Kilgallon,Michael. Enemy of Belief (2020) Fictional detective Ray King lives and works in Bispham. Ebook Amazon.\n*{{cite book|last=Rothwell|first=Catherine|title=Around Poulton, Thornton and Bispham in Old Photographs|publisher=The History Press Ltd|date=9 May 2002|isbn=0-7509-2952-9 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Bispham, Blackpool}}\n\n{{Blackpool geography}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of Blackpool]]\n[[Category:Villages in Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Seaside resorts in Lancashire]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Bispham, West Lancashire}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n |static_image=          Bispham_Seafront_with_Norbreck_Castle_in_Distance_-_geograph.org.uk_-_33113.jpg\n |static_image_caption=  Bispham Seafront with Norbreck Castle in the distance\n |official_name=             Bispham\n |unitary_england=           [[Blackpool]]\n |lieutenancy_england=       [[Lancashire]]\n |region=                    North West England\n |country=                   England\n |coordinates = {{coord|53.852|-3.041|display=inline,title}}\n | population = 20,001\n | population_ref = [[United Kingdom Census 2011|2011 Census]]\n |constituency_westminster=  [[Blackpool North and Cleveleys (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackpool North and Cleveleys]]\n |post_town=                 BLACKPOOL\n |postcode_area=             FY\n |postcode_district=         FY2\n |dial_code=                 01253\n |os_grid_reference=         SD309399<!-- NOT SURE WHERE THE EXACT CENTRE OF BISPHAM SHOULD BE, THIS IS POSSIBLY NOT TOTALLY ACCURATE -->\n |pushpin_map              = United Kingdom Blackpool\n |pushpin_map_caption      = Location in Blackpool\n }}\n\n'''Bispham''' {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|b|\u026a|s|p|\u0259m}} is a village on the [[Fylde coast]] in [[Lancashire]], England, a mile and a half north of [[Blackpool]] town centre.\n\n==Geography and administration==\nThe village is part of the borough of Blackpool. To the south of Bispham is Warbreck, North Shore and [[Layton, Blackpool|Layton]], to the east is [[Carleton, Lancashire|Carleton]] and to the north is Norbreck and [[Thornton Cleveleys]] and to the west, the [[Irish Sea]]. The area is mostly urban. Bispham was formerly in the [[Blackpool North and Fleetwood (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackpool North and Fleetwood parliamentary constituency]], but, as of the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]] forms part of the [[Blackpool North and Cleveleys (UK Parliament constituency)|Blackpool North and Cleveleys constituency]] whose [[Member of Parliament|M.P.]] is [[Paul Maynard]].\n\nThe village is in the [[North West England (European Parliament constituency)|North West England European parliament constituency]].\n\nBispham has three Blackpool Council [[Ward (country subdivision)|electoral wards]]: Bispham, Greenlands and Ingthorpe.<ref name=\"BC001\">{{cite web | title = Ward map | publisher = Blackpool Council | url = http://www.blackpool.gov.uk/Services/A-F/CouncillorsInformation/WardMap.htm | accessdate =12 January 2008 }}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nThe population at the [[United Kingdom Census 2001]] was 19,165, 13.41% of the population of Blackpool (142,900), with 3,873 residents aged between 0 and 17 years old (20.21%), 4,329 aged 65 and over (22.58%) and 10,963 between the ages of 18 and 64 (57.21%).<ref name=\"blackpoolresidents\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blackpool.gov.uk/NR/rdonlyres/953ABC47-4FC2-498F-A513-E919B3CE44BF/0/ThedistributionofresidentswithinBlackpoolv2.pdf |title=The distribution of Residents within Blackpool |date=July 2004 |publisher=Blackpool Council |format=PDF |accessdate=5 November 2008 }}{{dead link|date=August 2017|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> At the census 2011 the overall population using the same three wards increased to 20,001.\n\nPopulation by ward \u2013\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Ward !! Population\n|-\n|Bispham || 6,375\n|-\n|Greenlands || 6,865\n|-\n|Ingthorpe || 6,761\n|}\n\n==Village history==\nA 12,000-year-old animal skeleton (the Carleton Elk) found with barbed arrowheads near [[Blackpool Sixth Form College]] in 1970 provided the first evidence of humans living on [[The Fylde]] as far back as the [[Palaeolithic]] era.<ref name=\"amounderness\">{{cite web |title=Who were the Setantii? |publisher=amounderness.com |url=http://www.amounderness.com/site/setantii.htm |accessdate=26 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080330043117/http://www.amounderness.com/site/setantii.htm |archivedate=30 March 2008 |df=dmy }}</ref> The Fylde was also home to a British tribe, the [[Setantii]] (the \"dwellers in the water\") a sub-tribe of the [[Brigantes]], who from about AD80 were controlled by [[Ancient Rome|Romans]] from their fort at Dowbridge, [[Kirkham, Lancashire|Kirkham]]. During the Roman occupation, the area was covered by oak forests and bog land.\n\nBispham, known until 1910 as Bispham-with-Norbreck,<ref name=\"BH53229\">{{cite journal| last = Farrer| first = William|author2=Brownbill, J| title = Townships: Bispham with Norbreck | journal = A History of the County of Lancaster| volume = 7| pages =246\u2013247| publisher = British History Online| year = 1912| url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=53229&strquery=Bispham| accessdate =12 January 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"BH53228\"/> was originally a village in its own right, pre-dating the town of Blackpool by several hundred years. In 1066 Bispham was part of [[Tostig Godwinson]], the Earl of [[Northumbria]]'s, Lordship of [[Amounderness]].<ref name=\"BH53189\">{{cite journal| last = Farrer| first = William|author2=Brownbill, J| title = Amounderness hundred: Introduction and map| journal = A History of the County of Lancaster| volume = 7| pages =68\u201371| publisher = British History Online| year = 1912| url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=53189| accessdate =12 January 2008}}</ref> It is featured in the [[Domesday Book]] of 1086 as '''Biscopham'''.<ref name=\"BH53229\"/><ref name=\"BH53189\"/><ref name=\"DDB001\">{{cite web| title = Domesday Book online \u2013 Lancashire| publisher = domesdaybookonline| url = http://www.domesdaybook.co.uk/lancashire.html| accessdate =12 January 2008}}</ref> (meaning ''Bishop's estate'' or ''Bishop's house'') Many of the settlements and villages on [[The Fylde]] were [[Anglo-Saxons|Anglo-Saxon]] settlements. Some though were 9th and 10th century [[Viking]] place names. The Vikings and Anglo-Saxons seem to have co-existed peacefully with some Anglo-Saxon and Viking place names later being joined together\u2014such as Bispham-with-Norbreck.<ref name=\"VB1252\">{{cite news|title=Blackpool History|publisher=Blackpool Tourist Office|url=http://www.visitblackpool.com/resources/files/125_2_Blackpool_History.pdf|accessdate=18 March 2007|format=PDF}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref name=\"BT001\">{{cite news|title=Historic Blackpool: Blackpool's History |publisher=Blackpool Tourist Office |url=http://www.blackpooltourism.com/blackpool-history |accessdate=18 March 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080131233124/http://www.blackpooltourism.com/blackpool-history |archivedate=31 January 2008 }}</ref> Bispham having the Anglo-Saxon place name ''ham''<ref name=\"LUOAC\">{{cite web|title=English Place Names |publisher=[[University of Liverpool]] Walking Club |url=http://www.luoac.co.uk/other/English.php |accessdate=12 January 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071215115350/http://www.luoac.co.uk/other/english.php |archivedate=15 December 2007 }}</ref> and Norbreck having the Viking place name, ''breck''. Bispham-with-Norbreck comprised three hamlets \u2013 Great (or Greater) Bispham, Little Bispham and Norbreck, with Anchorsholme (then Angersholme) part of Norbreck. Although the three hamlets were originally part of the Lordship of Amounderness, they were later divided with the [[Moiety (kinship)|moiety]] of Little Bispham and Norbreck being given to [[Shrewsbury Abbey]] and Great Bispham to the Lord of Warrington.<ref name=\"BH53229\"/>\n\n''Great Bispham'' was a part of the Lordship of Layton. In 1539, it was bought by John Browne, who sold it to Thomas Fleetwood in 1550.\n\nThe moiety of ''Little Bispham and Norbreck'' was given to the monks of [[Shrewsbury Abbey]] by Roger of [[Poitou]]. In the early 12th century [[Henry I of England|Henry I]] ordered Stephen Count of Mortain to hold the moiety \"free and quit of all customs, pleas and suits of the [[Hundred (country subdivision)|hundred court]]. A few years after, [[David I of Scotland]] confirmed the moiety \"to be held as freely as in the time of his predecessors.\" In about 1270 the abbot and convent of Shrewsbury granted Little Bispham and Norbreck to the Abbot and convent of [[Dieulacres Abbey]], who held the adjoining Rossall estate. After the [[Dissolution of the Monasteries]], it was granted as part of Rossall estate, in 1553 to Thomas Fleetwood. Thus by then all three hamlets were owned by Thomas Fleetwood.<ref name=\"BH53229\"/>\n\nIn 1326 the spelling of the village was '''Byspham'''. Bispham and [[Poulton-le-Fylde]] were the two main populated centres in The Fylde in 1500, though the area was sparsely populated.<ref name=\"Genuki\">{{cite news|title=Blackpool, Lancashire genealogy|publisher=[[GENUKI]]|year=2006|url=http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/eng/LAN/Blackpool/history.html|accessdate=4 April 2007}}</ref>\n\nIt was in Bispham that the first mention of \"Blackpool\" appeared, found in the Register of [[Bispham Parish Church]] in 1602 with the christening record of a child born on 22 September to a couple who lived \"''on the bank of the Black Pool''\".<ref name=\"Genuki\"/> In the 17th century The Fylde coast was divided into three parishes\u2014Bispham, Poulton-le-Fylde and Lytham. The parish of Bispham covered modern-day Blackpool and Thornton Cleveleys and comprised the townships of Bispham-with-Norbreck and Layton-cum-Warbreck.<ref name=\"BH53228\">{{cite journal| last = Farrer| first = William|author2=Brownbill, J| title = The parish of Bispham| journal = A History of the County of Lancaster| volume = 7| pages =242\u2013246| publisher = British History Online| year = 1912| url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=53228&strquery=Bispham| accessdate =12 January 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"VB1252\"/><ref name=\"MUK001\">{{cite web| title = Lancashire Parishes\u2014Distribution of Lancashire Parishes in the 17th Century| publisher = Papillon Graphics| work = Virtual Encyclopaedia of Greater Manchester| url = http://www.manchester2002-uk.com/maps/lancs-parishes-map.html#| accessdate = 12 January 2008| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080118204247/http://www.manchester2002-uk.com/maps/lancs-parishes-map.html%23| archivedate = 18 January 2008| df = dmy-all}}</ref> In 1877 a detached part of Little Carleton (then known as Horsemans Hill) was placed in Bispham,<ref name=\"BH53229\"/><ref name=\"VB1252\"/><ref name=\"BH53224\">{{cite journal| last = Farrer| first = William|author2=Brownbill, J| title = Townships: Carleton| journal = A History of the County of Lancaster| volume = 7| pages = 228\u2013231| publisher = British History Online| year = 1912| url = http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=53224| accessdate =17 November 2008}}</ref> then in 1883 the area known as ''Bispham Hawes'', which was at the south end of Layton, was detached from Bispham and added to Layton. The population of Bispham-with-Norbreck in 1901 was 985.<ref name=\"BH53229\"/>\n\nAlthough the village centre used to be thatched with a number of pre-19th-century houses, it was redesigned in the 1960s; only two of the old houses remain. Much of the housing today is of the design style consistent with that of the 1930s to the 1950s.\n\n==Modern Bispham==\nThe area is mostly residential with two main shopping areas. The main road at the hub of the village, Red Bank Road, houses a number of high street stores such as [[Sainsbury's]] supermarket. The main shopping area in Bispham is split into two distinct parts. Firstly, from the top of Red Bank Road at the junction with [[A584 road|Queens Promenade]], running halfway down Red Bank Road toward Bispham [[fire station]]. This area contains a mixture of local and tourist businesses including a relatively large number of restaurants, as well as a number of [[takeaway]]s and [[fashion design|designer wear]] shops. The other shopping area is based around what is known locally as \"the village\" which is the area beyond Devonshire Road roundabout behind Bispham [[Police Station]], where the shops are sited around a large outdoor car park. The village area also contains the handful of original cottages remaining in Bispham. There are also small shopping areas on Ashfield Road, Moor Park Avenue and Bispham Road.\n\n===Religion===\n[[File:BisphamParishChurch01.jpg|thumb|275px|Bispham Parish Church, All Hallows]]\nThere are two [[Church of England]] Parish churches\u2014[[Bispham Parish Church]], All Hallows Road, and Greenlands St. Anne church, Salmesbury Avenue and one Catholic Parish Church, St. Bernadette's church, on Devonshire Road. Other churches include The Gate Community Church, Bispham United Reformed Church, Springfield Greenlands Methodist Church, and Cavendish Road Congregational Church. An additional Methodist Church on Beaufort Avenue closed in 2017.\n\n[[Bispham Parish Church]] has an original Norman doorway<ref name=\"BH53228\"/> and is the Mother church of Blackpool.<ref name=\"BPC001\">{{cite web| title = Welcome to Bispham Parish Church| publisher = [[Bispham Parish Church]]| url = http://www.bisphamparishchurch.co.uk/| accessdate = 10 September 2007| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929090529/http://www.bisphamparishchurch.co.uk/| archive-date = 29 September 2007| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref> Greenlands, St Anne has an active healing ministry.<ref name=\"GSA001\">{{cite web| title = Healing Ministry| publisher = Greenlands, St Anne church| url = http://www.bisphamparishchurch.co.uk/| accessdate = 12 January 2008| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20080306013120/http://www.bisphamparishchurch.co.uk/| archive-date = 6 March 2008| url-status = dead| df = dmy-all}}</ref> Keajra Kadampa Buddhist Centre, a residential [[Buddhism|Buddhist]] centre and a member of the [[New Kadampa Tradition]] is located on Holmfield Road.\n\n===Education===\nThe village has several schools, including\n\n*'''Primary schools'''\n**Bispham Endowed Church of England Primary School, located on Bispham Road. The original school was housed in what is now the home of the local [[Sea Cadet]]s near to Devonshire Road roundabout. The school is connected to Bispham Parish Church, and the first school was founded in 1659.<ref name=\"BH53228\"/>\n**Kincraig Primary School, located on Kincraig Road close to [[Kincraig Lake Ecological Reserve]]. After an [[Office for Standards in Education|Ofsted]] report in 2001 in which inspectors described the school as having \"serious weaknesses\", the school rapidly improved and in 2004 it was named as one of the 200 most improved schools in England, as well as being the most improved school in Blackpool.<ref name=\"gazette1275236\">{{cite news| title = Things keep on getting better at most improved primary school| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 2 December 2005| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/Things-keep-on-getting-better.1275236.jp| accessdate =18 January 2008}}</ref> In 2007 the school was listed in the top 100 most improved schools in England.<ref name=\"gazette3561743\">{{cite news| last = Butler| first = Heather| title = New rise is a 'fantastic achievement'| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 2 December 2005| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/primary/New-rise-is-a-39fantastic.3561743.jp| accessdate =18 January 2008}}</ref>\n**Langdale Independent Preparatory School\n**Moor Park Primary School, located on Moor Park Avenue in the Moor Park area of Bispham.\n**Saint Bernadette's Catholic Primary School\n**Westcliff Primary School\n*'''[[Education in the United Kingdom#Secondary School|Secondary schools]]'''\n**[[Bispham High School Arts College]] (formally closed in 2014, demolished in January 2017)\n**[[Montgomery High School, Blackpool|Montgomery High School]]\n*'''[[Further education|Colleges]]'''\n**[[Blackpool and The Fylde College]] the large main campus of the college is located on Ashfield Road, Bispham.\n\n===Local attractions and amenities===\n[[File:Kincraig Lake01.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Part of Kincraig Lake, Kincraig Ecological Reserve]]The village has a few attractions, with the tram station and the highest cliffs on both The [[Fylde coast|Fylde Coast]] and the North West Coast. There are a number of hotels and guest houses mostly around the seaward end of Red Bank Road and on Queens Promenade. The Red Lion pub also houses a [[Premier Inn]].\n\nBispham has five of the fourteen [[Lancashire County Council]] designated Biological Heritage Sites (BHS) located in Blackpool,<ref name=\"BC002\">{{cite web| title =Biological Heritage Sites| publisher =Blackpool Council| url =http://www.blackpool.gov.uk/services/a-f/biologicalheritagesites/home.htm| accessdate =1 January 2008}}</ref> including [[Kincraig Lake Ecological Reserve]] which is located on Kincraig Road, with Kincraig lake and a wild fowl population, from which Kincraig Primary School takes its school crest.<ref name=\"KPS001\">{{cite web | title = Home Page| publisher = Kincraig Primary School| url = http://www.kincraig.blackpool.sch.uk/| accessdate =12 January 2008}}</ref>\n[[File:North Shore Golf Club01.jpg|thumb|250px|North Shore Golf course, with views of the Lake District hills, and the [[Norbreck Castle Hotel]] ]]\n[[File:Bispham Rock Gardens01.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Bispham Rock Gardens]] [[Bispham Rock Gardens]] is at the top of Knowle Hill on Devonshire Road and runs downhill toward the back of [[Bispham High School Arts College]] (formerly Greenlands High School for Girls), with views from the top toward [[Pendle Hill]], [[Beacon Fell Country Park, Lancashire|Beacon Fell]] and the [[Forest of Bowland|Bowland fells]].\n\n'''North Blackpool Pond Trail''' beginning at Holyoake Avenue and continuing as far as Moor Park Avenue covers a group of 23 ponds, a reed bed, a community orchard (on Salmesbury Avenue located at the former 'Higher Moor Farm') and a series of dykes /ditches, most of which are Biological Heritage Sites (important at a county level). A campaign by local residents and environmental groups led to the creation of a series of walks and interpretation boards along with a programme of events and volunteering opportunities though most of these 'walks' existed prior to their involvement and were produced by 'job creation' schemes. There are now significant opportunities for people to access and engage with the natural environment.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.northwest.groundwork.org.uk/lancashire-west--wigan/news--events/news/2012/success-for-pond-trail.aspx |title=Success for North Blackpool Pond Trail |publisher=Northwest.groundwork.org.uk |date=7 February 2012 |accessdate=15 March 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.is/20130423202541/http://www.northwest.groundwork.org.uk/lancashire-west--wigan/news--events/news/2012/success-for-pond-trail.aspx |archivedate=23 April 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[Moor Park, Blackpool|Moor Park]] runs adjoining Moor Park Avenue and Bispham Road. The park contains a children's playground, parkland, a (disused) [[bowling green]] and Moor Park Swimming Pool which is located in the northwest corner of the park. It has a 25-metre pool and a teaching pool.<ref name=\"B4ME001\">{{cite web | title = Moor Park Swimming Pool, Bristol Avenue | publisher = Blackpool 4 Me| url = http://www.blackpool4me.com/blackpool4me/community/yourarea/ingthorpeward/moor+park+swimming+pool.htm| accessdate =18 January 2008}}</ref> The ''Friends of Moor Park'' group was set up in January 2007 with the aim of restoring the park to its former glory including work on the footpaths through the park and the possibility of re-opening the disused bowling green as well as work on the children's playground.<ref name=\"Gazette1959284\">{{cite news| title = Residents' chance to enhance their park| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 5 January 2007| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/Residents39-chance-to-enhance-their.1959284.jp| accessdate =18 January 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"B4ME002\">{{cite web|title=Friends of Moor Park |publisher=Blackpool 4 Me |url=http://www.blackpool4me.com/blackpool4me/community/yourarea/ingthorpeward/friends+of+moor+park.htm |archive-url=https://archive.is/20070515144714/http://www.blackpool4me.com/blackpool4me/community/yourarea/ingthorpeward/friends+of+moor+park.htm |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 May 2007 |accessdate=18 January 2008 }}</ref> Other parks in Bispham include Cavendish Road Recreation Ground which has tennis courts, [[Association football|football]] and basketball areas and a bowling green, which has a Friends group\u2014''Friends of Cavendish Road Recreation Ground''.<ref name=\"B4ME003\">{{cite web | title = Cavendish Road Recreation Ground| publisher = www.blackpool.gov.uk| url = https://www.blackpool.gov.uk/Residents/Parks-and-community-facilities/Parks,-playgrounds-and-community-facilities/Cavendish-Road-Recreation-Ground.aspx| accessdate =21 January 2016}}</ref> In November 2007 with both funding and planning obtained, work started at Cavendish Road Recreation Ground on a new ''Kiddies playground'', aimed at children under seven years old; the new park opened in 2008.<ref name=\"B4ME004\">{{cite news | title = Fylde coast's latest fresh air fun park| newspaper = Blackpool Gazette| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/news/local/fylde-coast-s-latest-fresh-air-fun-park-1-426008| accessdate =21 January 2016}}</ref> Red Bank Bowling Green is located next to Sainsbury's and is owned by the adjoining Bispham Conservative Club. The green was originally a garden belonging to the house which is now the Conservative Club.<ref name=\"BCC001\">{{cite web|title=About us |publisher=Bispham Conservative Club |url=http://www.bisphamconclub.co.uk/page6.html |accessdate=18 January 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071012173521/http://www.bisphamconclub.co.uk/page6.html |archivedate=12 October 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nBispham library was opened on 5 May 1938.<ref name=\"VB1252\"/> Bispham Hospital is a purpose built 40-bed rehabilitation unit, located on Ryscar Way for elderly patients from The Fylde coast as part of [[Blackpool Victoria Hospital]].<ref name=\"BFW001\">{{cite web|title=Bispham Hospital |publisher=Blackpool, Fylde and Wyre Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust |url=http://www.bfwhospitals.nhs.uk/hospitals/bispham/where.htm |accessdate=13 January 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071026035849/http://www.bfwhospitals.nhs.uk/hospitals/bispham/where.htm |archivedate=26 October 2007 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> [[Trinity - the hospice in the Fylde]] is a specialist [[palliative care]] service for adults and children located on Low Moor Road.<ref name=\"TTH001\">{{cite web| title = What is Trinity\u2014the hospice in the Fylde?| publisher = Trinity\u2014the hospice in the Fylde| url = http://www.trinitythehospice.inthefylde.org.uk/index.html| accessdate = 13 January 2008| url-status = dead| archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080305115246/http://www.trinitythehospice.inthefylde.org.uk/index.html| archivedate = 5 March 2008| df = dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n[[Public houses]] in Bispham include The Highlands, The Albion, the Red Lion, the Bispham Hotel and the Squirrel Hotel. There are also two wine bars, Xanders in ''the village'' and Maddisons on Red Bank Road.\n\nAdmiral Point on Queens Promenade is a luxury housing development in a Grade II listed building. It was originally [[Miners' Convalescent Home, Blackpool|The Miners Convalescent Home]] and was built by [[Bradshaw Gass & Hope]] between 1925 and 1927. It was opened by the Prince of Wales on 28 June 1927.<ref name=\"VB1252\"/><ref name=\"gazette1225442\">{{cite news| title = Premier league homes| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 19 October 2005| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/Premier-league-homes.1225442.jp| accessdate =23 August 2007}}</ref> The home, which for many years was empty was redeveloped into luxury homes by housebuilders Persimmon Homes and is now known as Admiral Point, with 47 apartments, together with 112 apartments and homes around the grounds, with two new six-storey apartment blocks built flanking the main building, and housing behind it.<ref name=\"gazette803268\">{{cite news| title = New name for famous old seafront landmark| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 8 June 2004| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/New-name-for-famous-old.803268.jp| accessdate =23 August 2007}}</ref> In February 2006 it was revealed that sales of apartments in, what the company described as \"the jewel in the crown\" at Admiral Point had helped Persimmon Homes to record profits, such was the popularity of the new properties in the Grade II listed building.<ref name=\"gazette1368688\">{{cite news | title = Prom flats sale delight| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 28 February 2006| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/business/Prom-flats-sale-delight.1368688.jp| accessdate =23 August 2007}}</ref> In October 2005 it was revealed that several high-profile [[Association football|footballers]], including former [[Premier League|Premiership]] player [[Robbie Fowler]] as well as [[Jonathan Macken]], [[Mads Timm]] and former player [[Lee Sharpe]] had bought apartments at Admiral Point.<ref name=\"gazette1225442\"/>\n\nBispham was also the home of British independent [[sports car]] manufacturer, [[TVR]], one of the main employers in Bispham, before production ceased in 2007 under owner [[Nikolai Smolenski]]. In May 2007 it was announced that Midlands based businessman, William Riley was proposing to bring back car production to Bispham, with two cars planned for production at a new purpose built factory, which would be on Bispham Technology Park, the [[MG XPower SV]] and another Premium [[MG XPower]] roadster and coupe.<ref name=\"gazette2858553\">{{cite news| title = Car deal so close| work = [[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 7 May 2007| url = http://www.blackpooltoday.co.uk/blackpoolnews?articleid=2858553| accessdate = 23 August 2007}}{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> On 27 July 2007 Blackpool Council announced that the sports car production would begin within a matter of weeks, initially at part of the former TVR factory; with the company eventually moving to a purpose built factory which had already been leased from the council by William Riley.<ref name=\"gazette3067864\">{{cite news| title = Car production set to begin again in Blackpool| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 27 July 2007| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/Car-production-set-to-begin.3067864.jp| accessdate =23 August 2007}}</ref> Bispham Technology Park is a growing, modern, Office and Retail Park which is due to be expanded further in 2008 with the creation of Kincraig Business Park on a {{convert|3|acre|m2|adj=on}} site within the park together with an environmental project with green space area to protect wildlife including a pond.<ref name=\"gazette3506879\">{{cite news| title = 200 new jobs hope at business park| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 21 November 2007| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/200-new-jobs-hope-at.3506879.jp| accessdate =18 January 2008}}</ref> On 11 January 2008, local MP, [[Joan Humble]] cut the first sod at a ceremony at the new Kincraig Business Park with the first of forty plots being created at the new park having already been taken even before building work started.<ref name=\"gazette3665917\">{{cite news| last = Hyde| first = Nick| title = Hats off to start of new business era | work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 12 January 2008| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/Hats-off-to-start-of.3665917.jp| accessdate =18 January 2008}}</ref>\n\n[[Layton railway station (England)|Layton railway station]] was originally named Bispham railway station.<ref name=\"BH53224\"/> Both Bispham and Norbreck are separate areas of Blackpool. Although the two do come together annually for the ''Bispham and Norbreck Gala'' held in July of each year with a procession that winds through both Bispham and Norbreck starting and finishing at Bispham Gala fields,<ref name=\"gazette1632781\">{{cite news | title = Bispham and Norbreck Gala| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 17 July 2006| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/Bispham-and-Norbreck-gala.1632781.jp| accessdate =13 January 2008}}</ref> an open space which is owned by Blackpool Council with football pitches, a community centre, secure grazing area and with part of the land sublet to Blackpool [[Rugby union]] football club and a Golf Driving range. In 2007 local residents called for a covenant to be placed on the Gala fields to safeguard the land to be used for future galas.<ref name=\"gazette1632781\"/>\n\n===Blackpool Illuminations===\nRed Bank Road is at the Northern end of the world-famous [[Blackpool Illuminations]]. The area at Bispham Cliffs contains the famous tableaux displays, where there is a pathway for holidaymakers and locals to view the tableaux close up. The first animated tableaux were erected in 1932 running along the cliffs from North Shore to Bispham, and the Illuminations were extended to its current length running from Starr Gate to Red Bank Road at Bispham.<ref name=\"BT002\">{{cite web| title = History of the lights| publisher = Blackpool Tourism| url = http://www.blackpooltourism.com/?OBH=299&SCH=illuminations%20history&ID=0| accessdate =2 December 2007}}</ref> Some of the tableaux have sound and visual content that can only be viewed and heard by walking by them.\n[[File:Blackpool Tramway - Bispham depot headstone.jpg|200px|right|thumb|Headstone from Bispham depot]]\nThe tableaux also includes mixed media in the various large tableaux displays.<ref name=\"Gazette3138163\">{{cite news | title = Let there be lights| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 22 August 2007| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpool-illuminations-2007/Let-there-be-lights.3138163.jp| accessdate =2 December 2007}}</ref> The displays at the cliffs from North Shore to Bispham contain forty large tableaux holding more than 5,000 square metres in surface area. There is a pedestrian walkway running the length of the tableaux displays which are set back from the Promenade beyond the tramway. [[Blackpool Tramway]] runs along the entire length of the Illuminations and there are over one million lamps in the display.<ref name=\"VB305\">{{cite web| title = Illuminating facts| publisher = Visit Blackpool| url = http://www.visitblackpool.com/?OBH=305| accessdate =2 December 2007}}</ref> In 2007 the Egyptian tableau which includes Egyptian [[sarcophagus]], which eerily opens to reveal a mummified secret, returned after an overhaul. Also at Bispham on the clifftop was a new BBC Portal video screen.<ref name=\"Gazette3138184\">{{cite news | title = What's new?| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 22 August 2007| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpool-illuminations-2007/Whats-new.3138184.jp| accessdate =2 December 2007}}</ref> In January 2008 new plans were revealed to erect two new all year round, [[triumphal arch]]es at either end of the Illuminations, \"selling the Blackpool message\".<ref name=\"Gazette3670899\">{{cite news | last = Fleming| first = Craig| title = Begging bowl days are over| work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]| date = 15 January 2008| url = http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/Begging-bowl-days-are-over.3670899.jp| accessdate =16 January 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Blackpool Tramway===\n[[File:712 at Bispham.jpg|thumb|200px|A double-decker balloon tram on the promenade at Bispham]]\n[[Blackpool tramway]] runs along the length of the sea front at Bispham. In 1920 Blackpool Corporation took over the ''Blackpool & Fleetwood Tramroad Company'' gaining a further eight miles (13&nbsp;km) of track, and also three further depots including the Bispham Tram Depot on Red Bank Road, until it closed in 1966.<ref name=\"FTS001\">{{cite news|title=Blackpool Trams |publisher=Fylde Tramway Society |date=3 September 2004 |url=http://www.webtramways.com/fts/modules.php?op=modload&name=News&file=article&sid=20&mode=thread&order=0&thold=0&POSTNUKESID=bb03664365976e75a64321790f2f3237 |accessdate=3 November 2007 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071019044630/http://www.webtramways.com/fts/modules.php?op=modload&name=News&file=article&sid=20&mode=thread&order=0&thold=0&POSTNUKESID=c9b8d0c8d415e0c052455f834bbbc29b |archivedate=19 October 2007 }}</ref> Built in 1898, Bispham Tram Depot had room to house 36 trams on six tracks, after being extended in 1914 by the Blackpool and Fleetwood Tramway Company. A substation was built to the side of depot. The depot was used to receive pantograph cars in 1928 and Brush cars in 1940. The depot closed on 27 October 1963 but used as a store, ''Alpic Cash & Carry'' until the mid-1970s.<ref name=\"BCC001\"/> The building was eventually demolished to make place for a [[Sainsbury's]] supermarket. The Depots headstone was installed at [[Crich]]'s [[National Tramway Museum]].\n\n==Notable people==\n''[[Emmerdale]]'' actress, [[Kelsey-Beth Crossley]] was a pupil at Bispham High School.,<ref name=\"blackpoolgazette070227\">{{cite news|title=Teenager makes TV soap debut|work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]|date=27 February 2007|url=http://www.blackpooltoday.co.uk/ViewArticle.aspx?SectionID=5442&ArticleID=2081817|accessdate=5 May 2007}}{{Dead link|date=September 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and former ''Emmerdale'' actress, [[Hayley Tamaddon]] was a pupil at Montgomery High School. ''[[Coronation Street]]'' actress, [[Violet Carson]], [[Order of the British Empire|OBE]] lived in Bispham until her death in 1983. She is commemorated at Bispham Parish Church. Former ''[[Brookside]]'' and ''[[The Royle Family]]'' actor [[Ricky Tomlinson]], was born in Bispham on 26 September 1939.<ref>*{{IMDb name|id=0866870|name=Ricky Tomlinson}}</ref> English film-maker, [[Alan Entwistle (director)|Alan Entwistle]] was born in Bispham on 4 July 1961.<ref>{{IMDb name|id=1350291|name=Alan Entwistle}}</ref> The actor [[Tony Melody]] lived in the Greenlands area of Bispham for many years until his death in June 2008. Footballer [[George Berry (footballer)|George Berry]], born in Germany then his family moved to Bispham soon after he was born.<ref name=sentinel12509705>{{cite web|title=Stoke City legends: George Berry|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-legends-George-Berry/story-12509705-detail/story.html|publisher=The Sentinel|accessdate=28 January 2014|date=10 August 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221213316/http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Stoke-City-legends-George-Berry/story-12509705-detail/story.html|archive-date=21 February 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> \nFormer [[S Club 8]] singer [[Stacey McClean]] is from Bispham.<ref name=\"gazette5682905\">{{cite news|url=http://www.blackpoolgazette.co.uk/blackpoolnews/X-Factor-Stacey-is-flying.5682905.jp|title=X Factor Stacey is flying the Blackpool flag|last=Ettridge|first=Lisa|date=28 September 2009|work=[[Blackpool Gazette]]|accessdate=28 September 2009}}</ref> Prof [[Gerald R. Leighton]] was born in Bispham. Naturalised American actor [[John Mahoney]] was born here in 1940. [[Chris Richardson]], who is widely regarded as a local legend resides in the Bispham area.\n\n==Sport==\nNorth Shore Golf Club is located at the edge of Bispham with most of the golf course in Bispham. Tee Time Golf Centre Driving Range and nine-hole par three course is based on Fleetwood Road. Blackpool Rugby Union Football club are based in Bispham. Bispham Junior football Federation (BJFF) is based at Bispham Gala Fields. Blackpool Rangers also share this field.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|last=Cunliffe|first=Norman|title=Uncle Tom's Cabin: Bispham's First Centre of Entertainment|publisher=Fylde Historical Society}}\n* Kilgallon,Michael. Enemy of Belief(2020) Fictional detective Ray King lives and works in Bispham. Ebook Amazon.\n*{{cite book|last=Rothwell|first=Catherine|title=Around Poulton, Thornton and Bispham in Old Photographs|publisher=The History Press Ltd|date=9 May 2002|isbn=0-7509-2952-9 }}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Bispham, Blackpool}}\n\n{{Blackpool geography}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of Blackpool]]\n[[Category:Villages in Lancashire]]\n[[Category:Seaside resorts in Lancashire]]\n", "name_user": "Grimes2", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFurther reading:+space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bispham,_Blackpool"}
{"title_page": "Berkeley Eagles", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox rugby league club\n  | clubname   = Berkeley Eagles\n  | image      = Berkeley Eagles.jpg\n  | fullname   = Berkeley Sports Rugby League Football Club\n  | nickname   = The Eagles\n  | short name =\n  | colours     = {{color box|blue}} Blue <br /> {{color box|gold}} Gold\n  | founded    = 1955\n  | ground     = Berkeley Sports Ground, [[Berkeley, New South Wales]]\n  | capacity   =\n  | chairman   =\n  | Owner      =\n  | ceo        =\n  | coach      =\n  | captain    =\n  | premierships =<br />\nillawarra second grade \u2013 2010<br />\nillawarra under-18's \u2013 2002<br />\nillawarra second division \u2013 2005 <br />\nillawarrra second division \u2013 1969\n  | premiershipyears = 1969, 2002, 2005, 2010\n  | runnerups  =<br />\nillawarra under-18's \u2013 2003<br />\nillawarra second grade \u2013 2008\n  | runnerupyears  = 2003, 2008\n  | minorpremierships = illawarra under-18's-2003\n  | minorpremiershipyears = 2003\n  | spoons     =\n  | spoonyears =\n  | cap =\n  | mostcap =\n  | league     = [[Illawarra Rugby League]]\n  | season     = 2010\n  | position   = 5th (of 9), ''Finals:qualified''\n  | current    =\n  | homejersey =\n  | awayjersey =\n}}The '''Berkeley Eagles''' are an [[Australia]]n [[rugby league]] football team based in [[Berkeley, New South Wales|Berkeley]], a country town of the [[Illawarra]] region. The club are a part of [[Country Rugby League]] and has competed in the [[Illawarra Rugby League|Illawarra]]  competition.\n\n==History==\n===Name and Emblem===\nThe Eagles logo consists of the name \"Eagles\" in large font, with the name \"Berkeley Sports\" in smaller font above it. Underneath lies a picture of a white eagle. The font is in the team's colours.\n\nThe Berkeley Sports Eagles RLFC was formed in 1955 in the Illawarra juniors league and in 1965\na senior team was formed in [[Illawarra Rugby League|Illawarra District Rugby League.]]\n\n===Colours===\nThe team's colours are blue and gold.\n\n==Honours==\n===Team===\n* '''[[Illawarra Rugby League]] Premierships: 2010 Second grade'''\n\n===Individuals===\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?client=7-2373-21087-55841-0 Berkeley Eagles Homepage]\n* [http://crlnsw.com.au/ Country Rugby League Homepage]\n* [[Country Rugby League]]\n* [http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?assoc=2373&pID=7 Illawarra Rugby League Homepage]\n* [[Illawarra Rugby League]]\n\n{{Illawarra Rugby League}}\n{{Country Rugby League}}\n{{Rugby_League_in_New_South_Wales}}\n\n[[Category:Rugby league teams in Wollongong]]\n[[Category:Rugby clubs established in 1955]]\n[[Category:1955 establishments in Australia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox rugby league club\n  | clubname   = Berkeley Eagles\n  | image      = Berkeley Eagles.jpg\n  | fullname   = Berkeley Sports Rugby League Football Club\n  | nickname   = The Eagles\n  | short name =\n  | colours     = {{color box|blue}} Blue <br /> {{color box|gold}} Gold\n  | founded    = 1955\n  | ground     = Berkeley Sports Ground, [[Berkeley, New South Wales]]\n  | capacity   =\n  | chairman   =\n  | Owner      =\n  | ceo        =\n  | coach      =\n  | captain    =\n  | premierships =<br />\nillawarra second grade \u2013 2010<br />\nillawarra under-18's \u2013 2002<br />\nillawarra second division \u2013 2005 <br />\nillawarrra second division \u2013 1969\n  | premiershipyears = 1969, 2002, 2005, 2010\n  | runnerups  =<br />\nillawarra under-18's \u2013 2003<br />\nillawarra second grade \u2013 2008\n  | runnerupyears  = 2003, 2008\n  | minorpremierships = illawarra under-18's-2003\n  | minorpremiershipyears = 2003\n  | spoons     =\n  | spoonyears =\n  | cap =\n  | mostcap =\n  | league     = [[Illawarra Rugby League]]\n  | season     = 2010\n  | position   = 5th (of 9), ''Finals:qualified''\n  | current    =\n  | homejersey =\n  | awayjersey =\n}}The '''Berkeley Eagles''' are an [[Australia]]n [[rugby league]] football team based in [[Berkeley, New South Wales|Berkeley]], a country town of the [[Illawarra]] region. The club are a part of [[Country Rugby League]] and has competed in the [[Illawarra Rugby League|Illawarra]]  competition.\n\n==History==\n===Name and Emblem===\nThe Eagles logo consists of the name \"Eagles\" in large font, with the name \"Berkeley Sports\" in smaller font above it. Underneath lies a picture of a white eagle. The font is in the teams colours.\n\nThe Berkeley Sports Eagles RLFC was formed in 1955 in the Illawarra juniors league and in 1965\na senior team was formed in [[Illawarra Rugby League|Illawarra District Rugby League.]]\n\n===Colours===\nThe team's colours are blue and gold.\n\n==Honours==\n===Team===\n* '''[[Illawarra Rugby League]] Premierships: 2010 Second grade'''\n:: \n\n\n===Individuals===\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Sports}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.sportingpulse.com/club_info.cgi?client=7-2373-21087-55841-0 Berkeley Eagles Homepage]\n* [http://crlnsw.com.au/ Country Rugby League Homepage]\n* [[Country Rugby League]]\n* [http://www.sportingpulse.com/assoc_page.cgi?assoc=2373&pID=7 Illawarra Rugby League Homepage]\n* [[Illawarra Rugby League]]\n\n{{Illawarra Rugby League}}\n{{Country Rugby League}}\n{{Rugby_League_in_New_South_Wales}}\n\n[[Category:Rugby league teams in Wollongong]]\n[[Category:Rugby clubs established in 1955]]\n[[Category:1955 establishments in Australia]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo/generalfixes, replaced: teams colours \u2192 team's colours", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berkeley_Eagles"}
